\subsection{New-User Operations Guide: Kibana, Rule Files, and \texttt{suricata.yaml}}
Where the preceding sections cover \emph{what} the IDPS is and \emph{how it is
installed automatically}, this section is a plain-language, hands-on companion for
the person who has to \emph{use} the system day to day. Assuming the automated
deployment in Section~5.4 has completed, it walks a first-time operator through
the three things they touch most often: the \textbf{Kibana} dashboard, the
Suricata \textbf{rule file}, and the master \texttt{suricata.yaml} configuration.
No prior Linux or SIEM experience is assumed. Any part of a command that is
specific to \emph{your} machine---an IP address, folder name, or path---is
flagged as \textbf{[change this]}; replace it with the value for your own
environment before running the command.

\begin{notebox}
\textbf{Path convention used in this guide.} All deployment scripts and the
\texttt{suricata\_temp.yaml} template are assumed to live together in a single
\emph{master script folder} on the Desktop, written here as
\texttt{\textasciitilde/Desktop/master\_script/}. \textbf{If your folder has a
different name, substitute it everywhere it appears below.} At the start of every
working session, move into that folder once:
\begin{lstlisting}[language=bash, caption=Move into the master script folder on the Desktop]
# The '~' symbol is a shortcut for your home directory (/home/<username>)
cd ~/Desktop/master_script      # [change this] to your real folder name
ls -l                           # you should see setup_script.sh and the .yaml template here
\end{lstlisting}
If \texttt{cd} reports \texttt{No such file or directory}, the folder name is
different---list your Desktop with \texttt{ls \textasciitilde/Desktop} to find
the correct name and use that instead.
\end{notebox}

