Reading Figure~\ref{fig:kibana_dashboard} from left to right, a new user should
recognise four things:
\begin{itemize}
 \item \textbf{Alert Signature} --- the human-readable name of the detection
rule that fired (e.g.\ \emph{ET SCAN Nmap -sS Scan}). This tells you \emph{what}
was seen.
 \item \textbf{Alert Category} --- the class of activity (e.g.\ \emph{Active
Scanning}, \emph{Attempted Denial of Service}). This tells you \emph{how serious}
it is likely to be.
 \item \textbf{Count} --- how many times that signature fired in the selected
time window. A sudden spike in a count is often the first sign worth
investigating.
 \item \textbf{Time range picker} (top right, e.g.\ \emph{Last 15 minutes}) ---
controls the window of data shown. Widen it to \emph{Last 24 hours} or \emph{Last
7 days} to see longer-term trends, and click \textbf{Refresh} to reload.
\end{itemize}

\begin{stepbox}{C --- A new operator's first minutes in Kibana}
Open the left-hand (``hamburger'') menu and choose \textbf{Discover}; set the
index pattern to \texttt{filebeat-*}, the time range to \textbf{Last 24 hours},
and click \textbf{Refresh}. In the \textbf{KQL} bar, a query such as
\texttt{event.severity <= 2} narrows the view to the most serious alerts; click
any row to expand it and read the source IP, destination IP, and matching
signature.
\end{stepbox}

\begin{notebox}
Kibana is \textbf{read-only} from a security standpoint: browsing dashboards,
searching, and filtering never changes what Suricata detects or blocks. A new
analyst can explore freely without risk of altering the sensor's behaviour.
\end{notebox}

