\subsubsection{Suricata Rule Files: How Detection Logic Is Written}
A \textbf{rule} (or \emph{signature}) is a single line of text that tells
Suricata exactly what pattern of network traffic to watch for and what to do when
it sees it. Rules are grouped into \textbf{rule files}. The large, regularly
updated rulesets fetched by \texttt{suricata-update} are stored under
\texttt{/var/lib/suricata/rules/}, while your own site-specific,
hand-written rules belong in a single dedicated file:
\texttt{local.rules}.

\paragraph{How to open the rule file.}
The custom rule file is opened with the \texttt{nano} text editor and superuser
rights (because it lives in a system directory):
\begin{cmdbox}{sudo nano /var/lib/suricata/rules/local.rules}
\begin{lstlisting}[language=bash, caption=Open the custom Suricata rule file]
sudo nano /var/lib/suricata/rules/local.rules
\end{lstlisting}
\textbf{Directory notes:}
\begin{itemize}
 \item \texttt{/var/lib/suricata/rules/} is the \emph{default} rule directory. If
you changed \texttt{default-rule-path} inside \texttt{suricata.yaml}, open the
rule file under \emph{that} path instead \textbf{[change this]}.
 \item If you prefer to keep an editable master copy of your rules alongside the
deployment scripts, it lives in the master script folder on the Desktop:
\texttt{\textasciitilde/Desktop/master\_script/local.rules} \textbf{[change
this]} to your folder name. Edit that copy, then deploy it with:
\begin{lstlisting}[language=bash, caption=Deploy a rule file kept in the master script folder]
cd ~/Desktop/master_script                                   # [change this]
sudo cp local.rules /var/lib/suricata/rules/local.rules      # copy into place
\end{lstlisting}
\end{itemize}
\end{cmdbox}

