\subsubsection{The Master Configuration File: \texttt{/etc/suricata/suricata.yaml}}
If the rule file defines \emph{what} to look for, \texttt{suricata.yaml} defines
\emph{everything else}: which network to treat as ``home,'' which interface to
watch, where to write logs, which protocol parsers to enable, and---critically
for this project---the format of the EVE JSON output that feeds the Elastic
Stack. It is the single most important configuration file in the deployment.

The file is written in \textbf{YAML}, a format in which \textbf{indentation is
significant}. Alignment is created with \textbf{spaces only---never tabs}. A
misaligned line is the most common cause of a configuration that will not load.

\paragraph{How to open the configuration file.}
\begin{cmdbox}{sudo nano /etc/suricata/suricata.yaml}
\begin{lstlisting}[language=bash, caption=Open the active Suricata configuration]
sudo nano /etc/suricata/suricata.yaml
\end{lstlisting}
\textbf{Directory notes:}
\begin{itemize}
 \item \texttt{/etc/suricata/suricata.yaml} is the \textbf{live} file that
Suricata reads at start-up. Editing it changes the running system directly.
 \item The pre-configured template that the installer deployed \emph{from} lives
in the master script folder on the Desktop:
\texttt{\textasciitilde/Desktop/master\_script/suricata\_temp.yaml}
\textbf{[change this]} to your folder name. To keep your baseline and the live
file in step, edit the template and re-deploy it:
\begin{lstlisting}[language=bash, caption=Edit the template in the master folder and deploy it]
cd ~/Desktop/master_script                              # [change this]
sudo nano suricata_temp.yaml                            # edit the baseline template
sudo cp suricata_temp.yaml /etc/suricata/suricata.yaml  # push it to the live path
\end{lstlisting}
\end{itemize}
\end{cmdbox}

